✅ Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics

## What was implemented

### 1. Installed @vercel/analytics package
- Added `@vercel/analytics` version 2.0.1 to project dependencies
- Used npm to install the package (matching the project's package manager)
- Updated package.json and package-lock.json accordingly

### 2. Configured Analytics in Next.js App Router
Following the latest official Vercel documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart):

**Modified: app/layout.tsx**
- Added import: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next";`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after the closing `</Providers>` tag
- This placement ensures analytics tracking is active across all pages while maintaining the existing component structure

### 3. Verification
- ✅ TypeScript compilation: No errors in layout.tsx
- ✅ ESLint: No linting errors introduced (app/layout.tsx passes cleanly)
- ✅ Package installation: Successfully installed 490 packages with 0 vulnerabilities
- ℹ️  Build: Pre-existing Supabase configuration issue (missing env vars) prevents full build, but this is unrelated to Analytics implementation

## Implementation Details

The Analytics component was strategically placed at the end of the body tag to:
- Ensure it doesn't interfere with the existing Providers wrapper
- Follow Next.js best practices for third-party scripts
- Maintain optimal page load performance

## Next Steps

After deploying to Vercel:
1. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard (Analytics section)
2. Verify tracking is working by checking browser Network tab for requests to `/<unique-path>/view`
3. Analytics data will appear in the dashboard within a few days of user visits

